## Beyond Layout: The Viewing Experience

In a [previous post](/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout),
I explored different photo gallery layouts and why I chose a cell-span grid
that gives landscape and portrait photos equal visual weight.
But layout is only part of the story.

This post documents the aesthetic refinements layered on top of that grid:
Polaroid-style borders that anchor color perception,
a double-border structure that handles bright highlights,
subtle rotation that breaks mechanical alignment,
and a neutral gray background that provides consistent color context.

You can see this implementation in action at [kadykov.com/photos](/photos),
and explore the [source code](https://github.com/kadykov/kadykov.com) for implementation details.

---

## Polaroid-Style Framing

The cell-span layout handles orientation equality,
but additional aesthetic refinements enhance the presentation
while providing practical benefits.

### Why Off-White Matters More Than You'd Think

Look closely at the Polaroid borders and you might notice something subtle: they're not pure white.
Instead, they're set to a light off-white — around 90–95% white.
This choice serves multiple perceptual purposes.

First, the border acts as a **white balance reference point**.
When viewing photos under non-ideal lighting —
warm incandescent bulbs, cool fluorescent lights, or miscalibrated displays —
both the photo and border shift color together.
The human visual system uses the "white" border as an anchor and recalibrates perception accordingly.
This helps photo colors appear more accurate despite environmental color casts.

Second, the off-white creates a **perceptual contrast boost**.
Against the deliberately darker, desaturated page background,
the viewer's eye perceives the border as "pure white" in context.
This means any 100% white elements in the photo itself —
clouds, snow, highlights — appear even brighter by comparison.
The effect increases perceived dynamic range:
whites feel more brilliant and blacks appear deeper.

Finally, because borders are CSS rather than baked into image files,
they compress better and introduce no artifacts around frame edges.

### The Double Border Structure

The border actually has two layers:

- **Thick outer border** — off-white, provides the perceptual "paper white" reference
- **Thin inner border** — light gray, separates bright photo areas from the outer frame

Without the inner border, bright photo regions —
clouds, snow, light skies — visually blend into the white frame.
This breaks our contrast illusion: the viewer can see that the border isn't pure white.
Even when both surfaces are technically "white",
but at different color temperatures, the transition looks unpleasant.
The thin gray separator solves both problems by making the boundary clear.

